{#
  EncryptionConfiguration consumed by the kube-apiserver via
  --encryption-provider-config. AES-CBC with a single 32-byte key
  protects all Secret resources at rest in etcd; the 'identity' provider
  is listed second so reads of any pre-encryption Secret continue to
  succeed during the one-time re-encryption pass that bootstrap.yml runs
  immediately after promoting the apiserver manifest.

  cluster/bootstrap.yml renders this file only when it does not already
  exist on the control plane, pulling the key value out of the
  'kubernetes/etcd-encryption-key' entry in the pass store on the Ansible
  host. The pass store is the canonical home for the key; the control-plane
  file is a regeneratable cache. To rotate keys, edit this file by hand on
  the control plane (and update the pass entry to match): add a new entry
  as the FIRST item under 'keys:' so it becomes the new write key, leave
  the previous one as the second so existing ciphertext can still be
  decrypted, then re-run cluster/bootstrap.yml. The play will detect the
  content change via its SHA-256 annotation, force a kubelet recreate of
  the apiserver pod, wait for /livez, and re-encrypt every existing Secret
  with the new key. Once the re-encryption pass completes, the old key can
  be removed from both the file and the pass store.

  Variables:
    encryption_key: 32-byte AES key, base64-encoded. Read out of the
                    operator's pass store by bootstrap.yml (and generated
                    there on first install). The rendered file and the pass
                    entry are the only two places this value lives — it
                    never goes to git, group_vars, or Ansible logs.
#}
apiVersion: apiserver.config.k8s.io/v1
kind: EncryptionConfiguration
resources:
  - resources:
      - secrets
    providers:
      - aescbc:
          keys:
            - name: key1
              secret: '{{ encryption_key }}'
      - identity: {}
